h discloses how her American interlocutors ingeniously fill this gap between the ideal and the real to live meaningful lives. The book also reveals that American culture, despite its seeming lack of guidance for those aging, plays a pivotal role in elders’ lives, simultaneously assisting and constraining them. Furthermore, Tsuji’s lengthy period of research illustrates major changes in her interlocutors’ lives, incorporating their declines and death, and significant shifts in the culture of aging in American society. The book also describes the author’s journey of getting to know American culture and growing into senescence herself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAgingxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aAgingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexSocial conditionsvCross-cultural studies. 0aOlder peoplezNew York (State)vCase studies. 0aSenior centerszNew York (State)vCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGlobal, Perspectives, Japan, Aging, America, Cross-culture, Research, Cultural Studies, New York, Upstate, Anthropology, Japanese culture, History, Pan-human, Experience, Values, Independence, Elders, Families, Self, Communities, Transliteration, Cultural values, Senior center.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881959740uhttps://www.degruy